With the first death from a new coronavirus, the UK is preparing to upgrade its prevention and control measures, which may include closing schools, cancelling large gatherings and working from home.

As of March 5, the number of confirmed cases in the UK had risen to 116. Compared with 51 cases two days ago, the number of confirmed cases has doubled in 48 hours.

The UK has devised a four-phase response to the outbreak and is now preparing for a second phase. The Prime Minister's spokesman warned that the virus was likely to "spread in a significant way. ". Local Chinese in the UK told interface news that the company was still on duty, but that handshakes between employees had been banned.

###First fatality, local infection?

A newly diagnosed patient in her 70s died Thursday at a hospital in reading, England, BBC News and the Guardian reported on March 5.

The patient, who had been in and out of the hospital several times for other illnesses, was tested Wednesday for a suspected new coronavirus infection, the hospital statement said. By the time the test results came back Thursday morning, the patient was dead.

Chief medical officer Whitty said the patient had not travelled overseas and was thought to have contracted the disease locally in the UK. The patient has not previously been in contact with a newly diagnosed patient, and authorities are tracing those who have had close contact with the patient.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: BBC

As the number of confirmed cases has risen, the UK has tightened restrictions on people returning from Italy, requiring all those returning from Italy to be quarantined at home if they feel unwell.

At the same time, the British authorities also announced that some of the confirmed patients will be treated at home, rather than sent to hospital. Of the 116 confirmed cases, about 45 were treated in isolation at home.

Whitty said it was "safer" for people with mild illnesses to be treated in isolation at home, with the help of medical staff, and that "anyone who needs to be hospitalized will be sent to a hospital" .

According to Susan Hopkins, Deputy Director of Public Health England's Centre for Infectious Disease Control, patients treated at home are in strict compliance with quarantine rules, many are quarantined in their own bedrooms, only to walk out of their rooms at mealtimes, pick up food and return to their rooms.

So far, 12 people have been cured in the UK. Meanwhile, at least eight of the confirmed patients, none of whom had traveled overseas or come into contact with other confirmed patients, had no known source of infection.

A spokesman for the British prime minister said authorities would continue to take measures to prevent the spread of the disease, "but it is now very likely that the virus will spread in a significant way. ".

Prime Minister Johnson reiterated that the UK was still in the first phase of its response to the outbreak, the "containment" phase. But medical staff have begun to prepare for a second phase of "delayed" proliferation.

###"FOUR-STEP" prevention and control facing a big test

In response to the new crown epidemic, the United Kingdom has developed a four-phase prevention and control program, depending on the development of the decision whether to upgrade.

The first stage is "control" , in the early detection of infected people, tracking close contacts, as far as possible to prevent the spread of new pneumonia. The strategy is to prevent the mass influx of people into medical institutions, resulting in a shortage of medical supplies.

But in preparation, hospitals have to prepare for the influx of patients, and each hospital has to prepare a quarantine zone; the authorities have also provided additional medical equipment and personal protective equipment for medical staff.

Britain has asked 30 hospitals to stand by for new crown cases. In the event of a pandemic, the 30 hospitals will cancel routine treatment and give priority to new patients with pneumonia.

The majority of patients are now treated at five specialist hospitals in England.

The second stage is "delayed" diffusion. If control measures fail and there is a surge in confirmed cases, the authorities will initiate a second phase of measures.

This stage is mainly to expand the "safe distance" between people.

Discussions are still under way within the UK government over what measures should be taken, including closing schools, restricting the use of public transport, stopping large gatherings and encouraging staff to work from home.

If the delay-and-spread protocol fails, the authorities will launch a phase III "study" -- Harvard -- to intensify research into how the virus spreads and how to treat it.

The British government wants to delay the peak outbreak of new coronavirus pneumonia until the summer to allow more time for research and the NHS to respond. The UK has already spent # 40m to develop a vaccine, which is currently in clinical trials.

The fourth stage is "de-stressing" . If the programme is launched, it means that the epidemic has spread in the UK on a large scale, which is the worst case.

By then, the pressure on medical institutions and society as a whole was "growing and clearly felt" .

Once this stage has been reached, the police will focus on the handling of serious crime cases and the maintenance of public order in the event of a police shortage.

The NHS will be open only to the seriously ill, and retired NHS staff will be recalled.

This phase of the programme is designed to ensure that those most in need of treatment are treated and that health-care workers are supported to mitigate the social and economic impact of the epidemic.

###The outbreak has spread, and we're out of protective products

Speaking to the health and Social Care Commission on Thursday, chief medical officer Whitty warned that epidemiological models predict the epidemic will spread across the UK in the near future, with the NHS facing 50 per cent of all possible cases in just three weeks, 90% in nine weeks.

To be ready, Whitty said, the NHS would need to delay some routine treatment until after or before the peak of the outbreak. Retired doctors can be recalled, and older retired doctors can take part in non frontline work, including counselling for the public on the NHS hotline 111.

On Tuesday, Whitty told reporters that the worst case scenario for the UK -- as if 80% of the population were infected -- could be much lower.

As for personal protection, Johnson said in a speech on the same day that the most important method was still washing hands with soap for as long as "happy birthday to you" twice.

He also stressed that for other people who are not infected with the virus, "we should do business as usual. ".

Cui, a chinese-american who lives in Leeds, West Yorkshire, England, told screen news that masks are no longer available, but no one wears them on the street. "My wife sometimes goes out to wear a mask, and I feel like someone is avoiding her, " he said.

When the masks ran out, a friend offered to sell them to trav for # 3550. TRAV didn't buy it. "I didn't think I'd need it. ".

Cui's company still works regularly, but employees have been asked not to shake hands with each other and to wash their hands before entering the office. Business lunch breaks have been temporarily closed and some overseas travel plans have been cancelled, but travel within the UK remains the same.

Because of the nature of the company, Xiao Cui believes that the future of telecommuting is unlikely. The company didn't mention telecommuting, either, and now it's just using space to make co-workers'seats more dispersed than ever before. The counters of local banks and police stations also began to discharge disinfectant.

Although close friends and colleagues often talk about the epidemic, Xiao Cui did not feel that everyone is very nervous. But in recent days, photos of sanitisers being snapped up in British supermarkets have been posted on social media, prompting Cui to exclaim, "it's a good thing we bought them early. ".
